# Session 2 - [1/22] - [Version Control and GitHub]

### Version Control
- Version control is a way to keep track of changes to files over time.
- Instead of saving many copies with different names (`essay_v1`, `essay_final`, etc.), version control records changes in an organized way. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

### Git
- **Git** is the most widely used version control software. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
- You can use Git on your own computer. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}
- It is better to store your version control online so you are less likely to lose your work. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}
- Major Git hosting providers:
  - GitHub
  - GitLab
  - BitBucket :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}

### Why Use GitHub?
- Track every change you make. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}
- Backup your code in the cloud. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}
- Build a portfolio that employers can view. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}
- Collaborate easily with other people. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}
- Host websites for free using GitHub Pages. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

### Summary
- Version control helps organize and manage changes to files. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}
- Git is a tool that implements version control. :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}
- GitHub is an online service that hosts Git repositories and adds features like collaboration and portfolio building. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
